prompt_used:
You are a WCAG accessibility expert.

The following HTML snippet has an accessibility violation:

<img class="rewardsIcon" style="height: 20px !important;
      width: 20px !important;
      position: absolute;
      left: -25px;
      top: -1px;
      max-width: 20px;
      max-height: 20px;" src="https://www.arabinstruments.com/static/frontend/Codazon/unlimited_sport/en_US/Mirasvit_Rewards/images/icon.png">

The failed rule is: image-alt

Here is the relevant WCAG guidance to consider:
Refer to WCAG 2.2 success criteria for this rule.

Using the information above, fix the HTML snippet to comply with WCAG. Also briefly explain why it was non-compliant.

fix_rag:
The HTML snippet provided is missing an `alt` attribute for the `<img>` element. The `alt` attribute is important because it provides a text alternative for the image, which is used by screen readers to convey the content of the image to users who are unable to see it. This is essential for users who are blind or have low vision.

To fix the accessibility violation, you need to add an `alt` attribute to the `<img>` tag with a descriptive text that conveys the same function or purpose as the image. If the image is purely decorative and does not convey any meaningful content, you can use an empty `alt` attribute (`alt=""`) to let assistive technologies know that the image can be ignored.

Here is the corrected HTML snippet:

```html
<img class="rewardsIcon" 
     style="height: 20px !important;
            width: 20px !important;
            position: absolute;
            left: -25px;
            top: -1px;
            max-width: 20px;
            max-height: 20px;" 
     src="https://www.arabinstruments.com/static/frontend/Codazon/unlimited_sport/en_US/Mirasvit_Rewards/images/icon.png"
     alt="Description of the icon's purpose">
```

Replace "Description of the icon's purpose" with an actual description that explains the icon's function or meaning. For example, if the icon represents rewards or points, the `alt` attribute could be `alt="Rewards icon"`.

This change makes the snippet compliant with WCAG 2.2 success criteria 1.1.1 (Non-text Content), which requires that all non-text content has a text alternative that serves the equivalent purpose.
